ooten’s department store in  he and a group of associates purchased the remaining sixty percent dillard’s enormous success with the texarkana store eventually launched a string of strategic store acquisitions in towns across the south beginning with magnolia columbia county in  and extending to tyler texas  and tulsa oklahoma  dillard moved his family to tulsa in  in  dillard turned his efforts back to his home state with the notable acquisition of downtown little rock pulaski county store giants pfeifer’s  and blass  dillard moved his family back to arkansas in  establishing little rock as the home base for his rapidly growing company dillard was quick to recognize the growing trend of the suburban shopping mall as the newest in retail destination shopping he opened his first mall locations in  in park plaza mall in little rock and southland shopping mall in tulsa dillard’s strategy of opportunistically purchasing troubled hometown department stores combined with entering new suburban malls became the pattern of the company’s growth for many years to come dillard often said that anything about an existing store could be changed except its location this vision enabled him to turn troubled retailers into huge opportunities for his growing company dillard’s muchanticipated grand openings were accompanied by legendary fanfare including promotions ribboncutting celebrations contests giveaways and more he embraced the hometown newspaper as the best means to reach customers in each of his markets and quickly formed a mutually beneficial partnership in each town in which dillard’s operated dillard was not only a pioneer of the suburban shopping mall but also of the use of technology in retailing at a time when most other retail operators viewed computers as mere novelties in the retail environment dillard’s success in consolidating and automating functions to create mass efficiencies served as the model for other retailers to study for years to come dillard won many awards and honors during his lifetime in recognition of his many achievements in  he was among the first four arkansas business leaders inducted into the arkansas business hall of fame dillard died at the age of eightyseven on february   in little rock he often said “business without integrity is not good business—and in the long run will not be successful” for additional informationarkansas business hall of fame  inductees online at httpwaltoncollegeuarkeduabhfasp accessed october   forgave reid “dillard’s founder chairman dead at ” arkansas democratgazette february   pp  a rosenberg leon joseph dillard’s the first fifty years fayetteville university of arkansas press  sales and marketing executives international “academy of achievement william dillard” online at httpwwwacademyofachievementorghonoreeswilliam dillardhtm accessed october   julie j bulllittle rock arkansas last updated  about this entry contact the encyclopedia  submit a comment  submit a narrative selected comments selected narratives william t dillard pfeifers building  business commerce and industry  modern era  through the present  the central arkansas library system  all rights reserved  web services by aristotle web design about the encyclopedia get involved resources helpful tips site map contact us browse entries browse media advanced search home